<subSubSection id="C37B19F4D735FFD70ABAACB77C257623" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDE4A7FD735FFD70ABAACB77C257623" blockId="14.[140,1108,765,1672]" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70ABAACB77E5E73F9" bold="true" box="[185,312,941,967]" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70ABAACB77E5573F9" box="[185,307,941,967]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6131FCD735FFD70B43ACB77D3273F9" authorityName="Ferris &amp; McFarland" authorityYear="2007" box="[320,596,941,967]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryolymnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracitaria">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70B43ACB77D3273F9" box="[320,596,941,967]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">Bryolymnia anthracitaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by its grayish-brown forewing with almost all of the basal and antemedial areas blackish brown and with a thick blackish-brown streak extending from the orbicular spot (in some specimens from the antemedial line) to the terminal line. The reniform and orbicular spots are outlined in black and the postmedial line is black but the lines are thin, so they tend to be partially covered and obscured by the prominent dark streak. Th e subterminal line is pale and usually obscure, being most evident near the costa because of black shading in the upper part of the subterminal area adjacent to the line. Forewing length ranges from 
<quantity id="4C99E79AD735FFD70A8FABDD7E6A74DF" box="[140,268,1223,1249]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" unit="mm" value="14.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="12.0">12–16 mm</quantity>
with males averaging 1.7 mm larger than females (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF0378ED735FFD70958ABDD7FAD753A" author="Ferris CD &amp; McFarland N" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" pagination="196 - 198" refId="ref8538" refString="Ferris CD, McFarland N (2007) A new species of Bryolymnia Hampson from southeastern Arizona (Noctuidae). Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 61: 196 - 198." type="journal article" year="2007">Ferris and McFarland 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In the male the hindwing is pale fuscous with darker fuscous on the veins, discal spot, and wing margin. In the female the hindwing is dark fuscous, slightly paler toward the wing base. 
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70B6EAA2A7D7B7574" bold="true" box="[365,541,1328,1354]" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
These are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6131FCD735FFD7095DAA2A7B2A7574" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" box="[862,1100,1328,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryolymnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biformata">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD7095DAA2A7B2A7574" box="[862,1100,1328,1354]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">Bryolymnia biformata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6131FCD735FFD70AD9AA4E7EEF7553" authorityName="Ferris &amp; McFarland" authorityYear="2007" box="[218,393,1363,1390]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryolymnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracitaria">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70AD9AA4E7F8D7553" box="[218,235,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70AF9AA497EEF7553" box="[250,393,1363,1389]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">anthracitaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the dorsal surface of the clasper is serrated, the clasper is without a basal dorsal process, the digitus is much larger and widens apically into a plate that is serrated on both sides, and the vesica is more globular with two stout cornuti. 
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70A8FAAA77E3E75E9" bold="true" box="[140,344,1469,1495]" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70A8FAAA77F8675E9" box="[140,224,1469,1495]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" reason="1">Female</emphasis>
genitalia.
</emphasis>
These also are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6131FCD735FFD708E4AAA77CBF75E9" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" box="[743,985,1469,1495]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryolymnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biformata">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD708E4AAA77CBF75E9" box="[743,985,1469,1495]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">Bryolymnia biformata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6131FCD735FFD70E38AAA47E7D75C4" authorityName="Ferris &amp; McFarland" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryolymnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracitaria">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70E38AAA47B2A75E9" box="[1083,1100,1470,1495]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70A8FAAFA7E7D75C4" box="[140,283,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">anthracitaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the corpus bursae is more elongated and the ductus bursae is completely sclerotized and markedly expanded anteriorly and posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37B19F4D735FFD70ABAA93C7D7876B9" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BDE4A7FD735FFD70ABAA93C7D7876B9" blockId="14.[140,1108,765,1672]" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70ABAA93C7E96767E" bold="true" box="[185,496,1574,1601]" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70ABAA93C7E36767E" box="[185,336,1574,1600]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6131FCD735FFD70BF9A93D7C76767F" authorityName="Ferris &amp; McFarland" authorityYear="2007" box="[506,784,1575,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryolymnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracitaria">
<emphasis id="B915966DD735FFD70BF9A93D7C76767F" box="[506,784,1575,1601]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">Bryolymnia anthracitaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from southeastern 
<collectingRegion id="49A5849DD735FFD70AE7A9507E5A765A" box="[228,316,1610,1636]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="14" pageNumber="201">Arizona</collectingRegion>
where it has been collected in oak scrub grassland. Collecting dates range from late June to late August.
</paragraph>
